-focus=\"#zDocsTopicActionsMobile\" data-target=\"#feedbackModal_main_2533800\" data-toggle=\"modal\" role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-feedback\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-feedback\"></use></svg><span class=\"zDocsFeedbackButtonText\"> Feedback</span></span></div></div><div class=\"zDocsTopicActionsMobile\"><button aria-label=\"Show topic actions\" data-toggle=\"dropdown\" id=\"zDocsTopicActionsMobile\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-ellipsis-h\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-ellipsis-h\"></use></svg></button><div class=\"dropdown-menu zDocsDropdownMenu zDocsTopicActionsMobileDropdown dropdown-menu-right\"></div></div><div style=\"flex-basis: 100%; height: 0px;\"></div><ul class=\"zDocsTopicPageDetails\"><li class=\"zDocsTopicPageDate css-cinqea\">Last Updated<span class=\"css-cinqea\">Sept 03, 2024</span></li><li class=\"zDocsAiTopicSummaryDetailsItem\"><button class=\"zDocsAiTopicSummaryButton\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-topic-summary\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-topic-summary\"></use></svg>Summarize</button></li><li class=\"spacer\" role=\"presentation\"></li><div class=\"zDocsLabelWrapper\"><ul><li class=\"zDocsLabel\"><a aria-describedby=\"hyperLinkFacetsTooltip\" class=\"css-ettsdk\" data-tooltip-content=\"Search all site by tag: Uniface\" data-tooltip-id=\"hyperLinkFacetsTooltip\" href=\"/de-DE/search?labelkey=prod_uniface\" stylesprops=\"[object Object]\"><svg aria-label=\"Tag\" class=\"ico-tag\" role=\"img\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-tag\"></use></svg>Uniface</a></li><li class=\"zDocsLabel\"><a aria-describedby=\"hyperLinkFacetsTooltip\" class=\"css-ettsdk\" data-tooltip-content=\"Search all site by tag: 10.4\" data-tooltip-id=\"hyperLinkFacetsTooltip\" href=\"/de-DE/search?labelkey=uniface_10.4\" stylesprops=\"[object Object]\"><svg aria-label=\"Tag\" class=\"ico-tag\" role=\"img\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-tag\"></use></svg>10.4</a></li></ul></div></ul></header><div class=\"zDocsTopicPageBody\" data-prismjs-copy=\"Copy\" data-prismjs-copy-error=\"Copy failed! Use Ctrl + C instead.\" data-prismjs-copy-success=\"Copied!\"><div class=\"zDocsTopicPageBodyContent\" dir=\"ltr\"><div id=\"zDocsAiSummaryContaineruniface_104xmz1665702891425.html\"></div><div><article class=\"hascomments\" data-page=\"bundle:uniface_104/enus/xmz1665702891425.html\" id=\"bundle:uniface_104/enus/xmz1665702891425.html\"><main role=\"main\"><article aria-labelledby=\"ariaid-title1\" class=\"dita\" id=\"xmz1665702891425\" role=\"article\">\n<h1 class=\"title topictitle1\" id=\"ariaid-title1\">\n      Handles for Communicating With COM Objects\n </h1>\n<div class=\"body conbody\" id=\"xmz1665702891425__handles_for_communicating_with_com_objects_112882\"><p class=\"shortdesc\">The <code class=\"ph codeph\">handle</code> data type in Uniface provides a mechanism to communicate with external objects via COM.\n </p>\n<p class=\"p\" id=\"xmz1665702891425__p_d35120e1_d35121e1_d35122e1\">Using an object's handle, Uniface can call-out to an external COM object, and an external COM object can call-in to Uniface.</p>\n<p class=\"p\" id=\"xmz1665702891425__p_d35123e1_d35124e1_d35125e1\">The <code class=\"ph codeph\">handle</code> data type is Uniface's equivalent of the IDispatch interface in COM, and holds a reference to an instantiated object. In the Signature Editor the underlying type of the <code class=\"ph codeph\">handle</code> data type is VT_Dispatch. The <code class=\"ph codeph\">handle</code> datatype can be passed to a function as an input or output parameter.</p>\n<div class=\"note note note_note\" id=\"xmz1665702891425__note_w5745ab1b5b7_w5746ab1b5_w5747ab1\"><span class=\"note__title\">Note:</span> In previous versions of Uniface, an instantiated object was addressed using the String datatype, because no special data type had been defined. In this case, the String data type functioned as a Uniface version of the IDispatch interface in COM.</div>\n</div>\n</article></main></article>\n</div></div><div class=\"contentPlaceholder\" style=\"height: 500px;\"><div class=\"contentContainer zDocsSideBoxes\"><div><h5 aria-level=\"5\" class=\"css-g931ng\">Related Links</h5><ul><li><a class=\"css-ettsdk\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/oxz1665702649123.html\" stylesprops=\"[object Object]\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-related-link\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-related-link\"></use></svg>COM and Uniface Parameter Data Types</a><p>Converting Uniface parameter data types to and from the COM environment has both a static and dynamic nature. When you export a COM Interface DLL, the data types of the signature definitions must be matched to the appropriate COM types, taking into account the user’s implementation selections. At runtime, both Uniface and COM allow the user to pass variants for parameters, so the connector can dynamically convert data types, within reason.</p></li><li><a class=\"css-ettsdk\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/vni1707830115353.html\" stylesprops=\"[object Object]\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-related-link\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-related-link\"></use></svg>Handles</a><p>A handle is a reference to an object, such as a synchronous component instance, entity, occurrence, or field. Handles can be used to call operations on the referenced object, or to pass these objects as variables and parameters.</p></li></ul></div></div></div></div><div class=\"bottomFeedback\"><div aria-labelledby=\"bottomFeedbackText\" class=\"bottomFeedbackContent\" role=\"group\"><span class=\"bottomFeedbackText\" id=\"bottomFeedbackText\">Was this topic helpful?</span><div class=\"bottomFeedbackButtonGroup\"><a data-backdrop=\"static\" data-target=\"#feedbackModal_bottom_2533800\" data-toggle=\"modal\" href=\"#\" role=\"button\" type=\"button\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-thumbs-up\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-thumbs-up\"></use></svg><span>Like</span></a><a data-backdrop=\"static\" data-target=\"#feedbackModal_bottom_2533800\" data-toggle=\"modal\" href=\"#\" role=\"button\" type=\"button\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-thumbs-down\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-thumbs-down\"></use></svg><span>Dislike</span></a></div></div></div><div style=\"position: fixed; bottom: 170px; right: 70px; cursor: pointer; transition-duration: 0.2s; transition-timing-function: linear; transition-delay: 0s; z-index: 3; opacity: 0; visibility: hidden; transition-property: opacity, visibility;\"><button aria-label=\"Scroll to top\" class=\"zDocsScrollTopBtn\" data-tooltip-content=\"Scroll to top\" data-tooltip-id=\"zDocsBackToTopToolTip\" id=\"zDocsScrollToTop\" type=\"button\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-next\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-next\"></use></svg></button></div></body></html>", "text": "Handles for Communicating With COM Objects Add to My Topics Add selected topic and subtopics Add Topic & Subtopics with topic head Add entire publication Watch Download PDF Save selected topic Save selected topic and subtopics Save entire publication Share Email Link Copy Link Feedback Last Updated Sept 03, 2024 Summarize Uniface 10.4 Handles for Communicating With COM Objects The handle data type in Uniface provides a mechanism to communicate with external objects via COM. Using an object's handle, Uniface can call-out to an external COM object, and an external COM object can call-in to Uniface. The handle data type is Uniface's equivalent of the IDispatch interface in COM, and holds a reference to an instantiated object. In the Signature Editor the underlying type of the handle data type is VT_Dispatch. The handle datatype can be passed to a function as an input or output parameter. Note: In previous versions of Uniface, an instantiated object was addressed using the String datatype, because no special data type had been defined. In this case, the String data type functioned as a Uniface version of the IDispatch interface in COM. Related Links COM and Uniface Parameter Data Types Converting Uniface parameter data types to and from the COM environment has both a static and dynamic nature. When you export a COM Interface DLL, the data types of the signature definitions must be matched to the appropriate COM types, taking into account the user’s implementation selections. At runtime, both Uniface and COM allow the user to pass variants for parameters, so the connector can dynamically convert data types, within reason. Handles A handle is a reference to an object, such as a synchronous component instance, entity, occurrence, or field. Handles can be used to call operations on the referenced object, or to pass these objects as variables and parameters. Was this topic helpful? Like Dislike"}